<FIRST>r a AM-TankerFire 1stLd-Writethru a0765 05-14 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0765,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Erupts on Tanker Carrying 450,000 Barrels of Crude</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with fire put out; picks up 6th
graf, `The cause...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire erupted Sunday aboard a Liberian
tanker carrying 450,000 barrels of crude oil, but U.S. Coast Guard
officials said the cargo was not threatened and the blaze was
extinguished nine hours later.
   ``The fire is safely out, there was no pollution and no
problems,'' said Lt.j.g. Robert R. Dubois with the Coast Guard in
Port Arthur.
   Two crew members aboard the 810-foot Jalinga were taken to Park
Place Hospital in Port Arthur for treatment of smoke inhalation
after the fire erupted in the vessel's engine room about 9:30 a.m.
Sunday, said another Coast Guard spokesman, Lt. j.g. Robert Garrott.
   The two unidentified men were being held overnight for
observation, Garrott said. No other injuries were reported.
   Two tugs were holding the Jalinga in place Sunday afternoon
while firefighters battled the fire, which was contained in the
engine room, Garrott said. It was extinguished about 6:15 p.m.,
Dubois said.
   The cause of the fire has not been determined, but Garrott said
the Coast Guard has begun an investigation.
   Garrott said the Jalinga originated in Galveston and was bound
for the Fina docks in Port Arthur. The ship is owned by Jalinga
Navigation, Inc., Monrovia, Liberia, he said.
</TEXT>
