<FIRST>r a AM-SoapSemiautomatic     05-14 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soap Semiautomatic,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Captured After Escaping Jail With Semiautomatic Carved From
Soap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERRY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jail inmate who made his second escape in
two months by pulling a gun carved from soap was captured Sunday in
a pecan grove.
   Roy Kenneth Sanford, 23, was caught while walking in the grove
south of Perry, said Houston County Sheriff Cullen Talton. He
escaped Saturday after he pulled what looked like a semiautomatic
weapon on three guards and ordered another inmate to open a
cellblock door.
   The gun had been carved from two bars of soap and painted black,
Talton said.
   ``At first glance, it looked like the real thing,'' Talton said.
``Of course, when you looked close you could tell it wasn't. He
even used an eye from a shoe, like you run shoelaces through, to
make the barrel look real.''
   Sanford, serving time for armed robbery and kidnapping, was one
of seven inmates who escaped from the county jail two months ago.
He was making a phone call Saturday when he asked jailer Clarence
Cash if he could get a drink of water from a cooler outside the
security door, Talton said.
   Cash let Sanford through, Talton said. Sanford went to the water
cooler, then pulled what appeared to be a gun, forced jailers to
lie on the floor and made his escape, Talton said.
   ``It's a situation that never should have happened,'' Talton
said Sunday. ``It's a case of jailers being negligent and not
following the rules of the jail.''
   Talton said authorities would consider disciplinary action
against Cash Monday.
</TEXT>
