<FIRST>r w PM-Coelho-Ethics Bjt   05-14 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho-Ethics, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coelho Defends Legality of Junk Bond Loan, but Says he Regrets it</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top House Democrat says an arrangement that
earned him $6,882 in four months through buying junk bonds with
other people's money ``wasn't worth the trouble'' in light of the
current focus on ethics.
   ``With the benefit of hindsight, I now regret having made this
transaction,'' Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., said Sunday as he
released his lawyer's report on the bond purchase.
   As House majority whip, Coelho is the third-ranking Democrat and
chief vote-counter for House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, who has
been charged by the House ethics committee with violating rules in
his personal financial dealings.
   Coelho, who could move up in the House leadership if Wright
falls, said Sunday he would be amending his 1986 financial
disclosure to include a previously unreported $50,000 loan that
financed half of a $100,000 investment in junk bonds in 1986.
   His lawyer's report said the chief executive of the savings and
loan that provided that financing had suggested the junk bond
investment to Coelho and then purchased the bonds on Coelho's
behalf when the congressman needed more time to raise the money.
   Junk bonds are high-risk, high-yield bonds often used to finance
corporate takeovers.
   According to his lawyer's report, Coelho first considered
investing his 1986 campaign funds in the 12 1@2 percent bonds,
based on a suggestion by Thomas Spiegel, chief executive officer of
the Columbia Savings and Loan Association of Beverly Hills, Calif.
   After Coelho decided against that investment for his campaign
treasury, Spiegel suggested that Coelho himself could make an
investment in the bonds, which were being issued for a takeover of
Beatrice foods arranged by Drexel Burnham Lambert.
   When Coelho could not come up with the $100,000 by the required
purchase date of May 5, Spiegel bought the bonds himself and held
them for a month while Coelho completed his financing. Half the
money came from Spiegel's thrift institution and the rest from two
other banks.
   At that point, Coelho bought the bonds from Spiegel and paid him
interest equivalent to what the bonds made during the period of the
loan. When the congressman sold the bonds in October 1986, he was
able to repay the loans and realize a $6,882 profit.
   In his report, attorney Robert F. Bauer concluded that Coehlo
did not violate House rules in his arrangement with Spiegel,
because the congressman paid interest and thus accepted no ``gift''
which might have been improper.
   The fact that the investment was issued at first to Coelho's
campaign committee, instead of the congressman, was a clerical
error, Bauer said. Errors in the reported dates of the transactions
might require Coelho to amend his 1986 tax returns, he said.
   ``We believe that the appearances presented by the transaction
can be properly addressed by a full disclosure of all surrounding
circumstances,'' he said.
   There is no indication whether the ethics committee is
considering or plans to review the bond purchase.
   Coelho insists Spiegel has asked for no legislative favors and
none were granted. Coelho said in his statement he was ``accepting
without reservations the conclusion of my legal counsel that the
purchase of the bonds was totally above board.''
   But, he said, ``public officials are today, however, living in a
period of intense questioning.
   ``With the benefit of hindsight, I now regret having made this
transaction,'' he said. ``I don't like it when my public decisions
or private actions raise questions, as this investment did, and the
$6,882 profit wasn't worth the trouble.''
   Coelho last year put all of his holdings into a blind trust.
   Coelho did not disclose the bond transaction with Spiegel or the
loan from Spiegel's financial institution when The Washington Post
last month first reported on his junk bond investment.
   David Dreyer, Coelho's press secretary, said the congressman's
staff had taken a month ``to understand fully and reconstruct this
transaction.''
   He said that effort did not include checking whether Spiegel had
any interest in legislation, since that indicates a violation of
House rules only if Spiegel had conferred a gift.
</TEXT>
