<FIRST>r a AM-TrainDerail 2ndLd-Writethru a0607 05-14 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Train Derail, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0607,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Remove Wreckage of Derailed Train, Four Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with investigators saying part
of braking system on two locomotives failed to work, more families returning
to their homes. Adds byline. Picks up 7th graf pvs: `The 69-car ...' ^By
LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   SAN BERNDARDINO, CALIF _ The braking systems were faulty on two
locomotives of a freight train that thundered down the steep Cajon
Pass, smashed into 11 homes and killed four people, investigators
said Saturday.
   National Transportation Safety Board acting Chairman James
Kolstad told reporters Saturday night that the so-called dynamic
brakes failed to work. But it was too early to tell if that caused
the wreck, he said.
   Locomotives have air brakes which apply pressure to the wheels;
dynamic brakes reverse the direction of the wheels, he explained.
   ``It appears a great majority of the cars were braking at the
time of the accident,'' he said.
   The search of the wreckage ended Saturday afternoon, and heavy
equipment began removing the twisted train cars that flew off
curved tracks into the homes Friday.
   The body of a crewman was found at 2:30 a.m., hours after a man
was pulled alive from his crumbled home. No one else was reported
missing.
   Twenty-nine families were evacuated from their homes because the
wrecked cars lay over an underground gas line. By Saturday night,
19 families still had to remain out of their houses, including
those houses hit in the derailment, said Theresa Schroeder of the
local Red Cross.
   The 69-car Southern Pacific freight hauling a sandy mineral
raced down 4,109-foot Cajon Pass between the San Bernardino and San
Gabriel Mountains, derailed on a curve and hit 11 homes about 7:40
a.m. Friday.
   The crew radioed to a dispatcher that it was out of control at
90 mph.
   ``The train was all over the place,'' said a witness, Al Dorame.
``It looked like a toy in a sandbox. ... Some of the people thought
it was an earthquake.''
   The dead were identified as stepbrothers Jason Thompson, 9, and
Tyson White, 7; conductor Everett S. Crown, 36, a 17-year Southern
Pacific employee; and brakeman Allan R. Reiss, 44, an 18-year
employee, whose body was not found until Saturday morning.
   Three trainmen and six other people were injured.
   One of the injured, Christopher Shaw, 24, survived for hours
under the wreckage. He was found Friday evening later in a pocket
of air under rail cars and the sandy cargo that crushed his home.
   He had surgery to have a pin put in a broken leg and was in
serious condition at San Bernardino County Medical Center, said
nursing supervisor Helen Ramirez.
   Officials of the NTSB, Southern Pacific, the Federal Railroad
Administration and the Brotherhood of Locomotive Engineers met to
coordinate the investigation, said NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz.
   Plans included on-site investigations and study of three event
recorders that monitored train functions. ``They will certainly
tell the speed of the train and might tell about brake
application,'' Lopatkiewicz said.
   Investigators will also examine the train crew's history of work
performance and whether there was evidence of alcohol or drug use,
he said. Surviving crewmen will be interviewed, but probably not
Saturday, he said.
   Shaw was half-asleep when his home was flattened. He lay there
all day and into the night before he was found, still conscious
beneath the rubble.
   Rescuers extended an oxygen tube and encouraged him during the
1{ hours it took to free him. Debris had apparently formed a cave
with enough oxygen to sustain him, said Gene Brooks, a rescue
supervisor.
   Shaw's mother, Maryann Shaw, watched nervously during the rescue.
   ``I was so confused,'' Mrs. Shaw said. ``I told him that his
mama was outside and I was out here for him.''
   The train was going from Mojave in the high desert to Long Beach
with a load of sodium carbonate and sodium bicarbonate, components
of potash, a mineral used to make fertilizer and soap, railroad
spokesmen said.
   The tracks were expected to remain closed at least a day,
forcing the detour of 15 freights and two passenger trains.
</TEXT>
