<HEAD>Riot Police Break Up Protest Over Student's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KWANGJU, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charging riot police lashing out
with truncheons and shields Sunday dispersed thousands of
protesters who marched for a second day to protest the death of a
radical student.
   About 5,000 riot police tore into a crowd of about the same
number in front of the provincial government headquarters.
Screaming protesters were trampled underfoot as troopers broke up
the crowd after some people tried to force their way past police.
   Radical students pelted police with rocks and bricks as fighting
surged up and down Kwangju's main street.
   Some police and protesters were hurt in the fighting. Police
officials said they had no figures on injuries.
   Protesters were marching to denounce authorities over the death
of radical student Lee Chol-kyu. Dissidents claim police tortured
and killed him.
   Lee's body was found Wednesday in a reservoir near Kwangju, a
provincial capital 170 miles south of Seoul. Police, who were
hunting Lee for anti-government acitivies, have denied any
involvement in the death.
   In Seoul, officials said pathology tests were conducted Sunday
to determine if Lee's body contained plankton, which they said
would suggest that he died by drowning. Initial results would be
released Monday, they said.
   Radical student leaders told a news conference Sunday they would
appeal to Amnesty International to conduct an independent
investigation of the death if an official Korean probe concludes
police were not responsible.
   Dissident leaders called during the protest Sunday for the
overthrow of President Roh Tae-woo's government and demanded the
expulsion of the 43,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea.
   The dissidents claim Roh and the United States are trying to
impose authoritarian rule on the country.
