<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 0938EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Israel     05-14 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Israel,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Approves Shamir Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Cabinet on Sunday approved Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's long-awaited plan for elections in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The vote was 20-6.
   The four-page, 20-point Shamir plan passed easily, largely
because it sidestepped controversial points such as foreign
supervision of elections, participation of 140,000 Arabs in east
Jerusalem and a timetable for the balloting.
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon led right-wing opposition to the
proposal. He was joined in voting against the plan by two other
ministers from the Likud Bloc members, two from the center-left
Labor and one from the National Religious Party.
   Sharon was quoted by an aide as telling the Cabinet it was ``a
sure recipe for more violence and terror'' and one that could raise
``a danger of war.''
   He was quoted by an aide as proposing his own seven-point plan,
which calls for extending Israeli law to Jewish settlements in the
occupied lands, an act equivalent to annexation.
   Sharon, a member of Shamir's Likud Bloc, accused the Cabinet of
rushing into a decision because of the presence of a U.S. State
Department delegation led by Dennis Ross, chief of policy planning.
   Ross met with four moderate Palestinians but 11 others boycotted
the meeting in Jerusalem. The key topic was the elections proposal,
which Palestinians made clear would have to be endorsed by the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Five Palestinians who did not attend sent a letter to U.S.
officials criticizing the Shamir plan as ``grossly deficient.''
   The daily Yediot Ahronot said U.S. officials pushed for a
timetable on elections. It said Shamir believed elections could be
held within one year while Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin estimated
six months were needed.
   In addition to the timetable, the United States urged Israel to
allow 140,000 east Jerusalem Arabs to vote and to permit
international supervision of balloting.
   Shamir's plan does not refer to either issue. It reportedly
calls for electing 10 Palestinians from the occupied territories to
negotiate with Israel on an interim period of autonomy, with talks
to begin after three years on the final status of the territories.
   Israel hopes the plan will help end the 17-month Palestinian
uprising in the occupied territories, in which at least 472 Arabs
and 21 Israelis have been killed.
   Israel captured the West Bank, Arab east Jerusalem and the Gaza
Strip from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. Israel
later annexed east Jerusalem.
</TEXT>
