<HEAD>Gorbachev Arrives in Irkutsk on Way to China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs with Gorbachev arriving in Siberian city.
Pickup 4th graf, ``Tass said ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev left Sunday for
Beijing and the first Soviet-Chinese summit meeting in 30 years.
   Gorbachev's morning departure, reported by the Tass news agency,
came a day early. He arrived in the Siberian city of Irkutsk, where
Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesmen in Beijing said he would rest
before continuing to Beijing on Monday. The spokesman spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Tass called the visit to Irkutsk a ``working stop-over,'' and
said he had a ``warm talk with working people'' at the airport.
   Tass said Gorbachev was accompanied by Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze, who just returned from a visit to West Germany,
and Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, alternate Politburo
member Yuri Maslyukov and Health Minister Yevgeny Chazov.
   The last Soviet-Chinese summit was in 1959 when Nikita S.
Khrushchev met Mao Tse-tung. Relations soured then as Mao
challenged the Soviet claim to leadership of the world communist
movement.
   Both sides expect Gorbachev's meetings with Deng Xiaoping will
normalize their governmental and party relations, and help ease the
remaining tensions along their 4,300-mile border.
   The Soviet Union announced last week that it will begin
withdrawing soldiers from its Mongolian ally on Monday, the day
Gorbachev's visit to China is to begin.
   Soviet soldiers were stationed in Mongolia, sandwiched between
the Soviet Union and China, because of border disputes that flared
briefly into fighting in the late 1960s.
