<HEAD>PRECEDE Beirut</HEAD>
<HEAD>German Returns To Office in Lebanon, 10 Days After His Reported Kidnapping</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with Berri, Quint comments. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZAHRANI, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German relief worker who
disappeared 10 days ago returned on Sunday to his organization's
headquarters.
   Markus Quint arrived at the ASME-Humanitas base in this southern
town of Zahrani accompanied by Nabih Berri, head of the Shiite Amal
militia.
   Berri, also the justice minister in Lebanon's Moslem cabinet,
said his militia obtained Quint's release from kidnappers, but he
refused to identify the kidnappers.
   ``I don't want to say anything that will hurt Quint and his
colleagues,'' Berri said.
   Quint, wearing a brown track suit and smoking a cigarette,
turned to the pro-Syrian militia chief and thanked him for his help
in his return.
   Quint disappeared on May 4. There had been no claim of
responsibility.
   Palestinian guerrilla leaders had said unidentified kidnappers
were holding Quint in connection with the case of TWA hijacker
Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   On Saturday, the West German newspaper Bild am Sonntag reported
Quint had signed a letter saying he was abducted in connection with
Hamadi case. ``The kidnappers are demanding a mild sentence for
Hamadi,'' it said.
   West German officials did not comment on the report.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, faces life in prison if
convicted of murder and air piracy in the June 1985 hijacking of a
TWA jetliner and the slaying of an U.S. Navy diver on board. He
confessed to the hijacking but denies taking part in the murder.
   He is on trial in Frankfurt, West Germany. A verdict that is
expected Wednesday.
   There are 15 foreigners held hostage in Lebanon, including nine
Americans. The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was seized March
16, 1985.
   In addition, Jack Mann, an elderly Briton, disappeared Friday,
and his wife said she believes he has been kidnapped.
   ASME-Humanitas is a private organization that provides medical
aid, mainly to Palestinian refugees in the camps of Ein el-Hilweh
and Mieh Mieh.
</TEXT>
