<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Israel     05-14 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Israel,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Israel and South Africa Involved in Technology Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper said Sunday that Israel's Mossad
secret service was involved in South African efforts to obtain
British missile technology.
   The Sunday Telegraph, a conservative weekly, attributed its
report to unidentified ``security sources in London.'' It said the
sources claimed Mossad and the South African arms manufacturer
Armscor were linked to an operation that led to the arrests of five
men in Paris last month in an arms deal.
   The report said, ``The ultimate goal of the Paris operation is
thought to have been for South Africa and Israel to undertake joint
development of a series of high-speed missiles for use by both
ground and air forces.''
   It claimed three of the men arested in Paris were Northern
Ireland Protestants who allegedly were negotiating with a South
African diplomat and a U.S. arms dealer to exchange British missile
parts made in Northern Ireland for South African arms.
   According to the newspaper, the plan involved smuggling parts of
the shoulder-launched Blowpipe missile to South Africa to enable
Armscor to develop its own missiles. It said Mossad wanted to
acquire the technology for Britain's Starstreak missile.
   Both the Blowpipe and Starstreak missiles are made at the Short
Brothers factory in Belfast, Northern Ireland.
   The Sunday Telegraph said Britain's MI6 intelligence service was
trying to determine how Protestant activists in Northern Ireland
received arms believed to have been purchased with South African
money and shipped through militia groups in Lebanon.
   ``It is here that sources believe Mossad actively assisted with
the South African operation,'' the newspaper said.
   Protestant and Roman Catholic militants have been battling in
Northern Ireland for nearly 20 years. The Catholics want to unite
the British province, where Protestants outnumber Caholics 3-2,
with the predominantly Catholic Irish Republic.
