<HEAD>Sakharov Calls for Democracy, Criticizes Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activist Andrei Sakharov said
Sunday that the reforms of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
have not gone far enough to cure an ailing economy or bring
democracy.
   The 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner flew to Italy on Saturday with
his wife, Yelena Bonner, to speak at an Italian Socialist Party
congress in the northern city of Milan.
   Sakharov, who was recently elected to the new Soviet parliament,
said that while Gorbachev's reforms were ``moving in the right
direction'' in foreign affairs, ``there are many aspects that are
causing profound distress.''
   ``Economic reforms go ever more slowly and the people are losing
interest in their work because they can't buy anything,'' he said.
   He said the stagnation was occurring because the government
dismantled old bureaucratic structures but has not created new ones.
   The 67-year-old physicist criticized Gorbachev for emergency
measures he had taken to limit demonstrations in the wake of
nationalist uprisings.
   ``We are in a blind alley, and there have been various political
decisions taken lately which I will not hesitate to define as
anti-democratic,'' he said.
   Sakharov was detained for nearly seven years in the northern
city of Gorky after he criticized the Soviets' 1979 military
intervention in Afghanistan.
