<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     05-14 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Grows in Kwangju as Grim Anniversary Nears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KWANGJU, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot troops Sunday broke up a march
by thousands of people protesting the death of a radical student
they claim was tortured and killed by police.
   Police used clubs and shields on the crowd of about 5,000 who
gathered outside the provincial government headquarters in Kwangju,
170 miles southwest of Seoul.
   Some protesters were trampled as people tried to force their way
past police. Injuries were seen during the violent confrontation
but police said they had no figures.
   Radical students pelted police with rocks and bricks as fighting
surged up and down Kwangju's main street. Hundreds of onlookers
jeered and yelled insults as police tried to clear the street by
marching in lines with interlocked shields.
   ``Down with the military dictatorship!'' protesters chanted.
``Drive out the Yankees!''
   A larger but less-violent protest was held Saturday, and a march
by about 1,000 people earlier on Sunday was peaceful.
   The marches were called by radical students to protest the death
of Lee Chul-kyu, whose body was found Wednesday in a reservoir near
Kwangju.
   Authorities fear Lee's death will keep heightening tensions in
Kwangju, which marks the anniversary this week of the May 18, 1980,
uprising in which at least 192 people were killed. Many students
blame President Roh Tae-woo, a former military general, for the
bloody suppression of the uprising.
   All police in Kwangju and nearby areas were put on special alert.
   Dissidents claim Lee, who was being sought by police for
anti-government activities, was tortured to death by authorities.
Police said an autopsy last week showed no signs of torture and
that pathology tests Sunday confirmed the existence of plankton in
his body, indicating death by drowning.
   To ensure the credibility of the tests, authorities allowed two
independent medical experts and opposition lawmakers to take part
in or witness the process.
   Radical student leaders told reporters they would appeal to
Amnesty International, the London-based human rights group, to
conduct an independent investigation if the official Korean probe
concluded police were blameless.
   Kim Hyung-jang, one of the student leaders, claimed government
pathologists were helping cover up police involvement. ``We cannot
trust them,'' he told the news conference.
   During the march, dissidents called for the overthrow of Roh and
demanded the expulsion of the 43,000 U.S. troops based in South
Korea.
   The dissidents claim Roh and the United States are trying to
impose authoritarian rule on the country.
   Radical students and dissidents, estimated by government
officials at 10,000, are a well-organized minority in South Korea's
42 million population. But they lack public support because of
their violent tactics and extreme views.
</TEXT>
