<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-14 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young bicyclists who break the law this
summer will be hauled off to Bicycle Court for a spin on the wheels
of justice.
   Those convicted won't be put on a chain gang, but they could be
sentenced to a week with crayons and a coloring book full of safety
hints.
   The kids' court was designed to simulate the legal system and
teach youths a lesson in safety. The program was discontinued last
year, when youths served as judge and jury, but has been revamped
by the police department in time for this summer, safety officer
Jerry Kittel said.
   This time, a police officer will mete out justice, Kittel said.
   ``Some kids got let go because they were friends with the kids
serving as court officers,'' he said. ``Others got pretty stiff
penalties because they were not friends with the kids serving on
the court.''
   Children age 7 to 9 who are convicted in Bicycle Court this year
must color a safety coloring book. Youths 10 to 13 must write
essays on bicycle safety.
   Each has one week to complete the ``sentence.''
   Bicycle Court will be held at the police station once a week
beginning later this month. Kittel said he expects a full court
docket once school gets out.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city claimed champion status in
the battle of the breakfasts when 33,869 locals turned out to dine
on thousands of pounds of pancakes washed down with 600 gallons of
coffee.
   Springfield claimed the title of world's biggest breakfast
Saturday morning when volunteers who had spent 12 hours mixing
pancake batter served up a four-hour meal that would not have won
approval from Weight Watchers.
   The pancake recipe included 3,000 pounds of flour, 600 egg yolks
and 400 gallons of water. The final product was drenched in 200
gallons of maple syrup.
   ``We're getting it down to a science,'' said Amy Barron, a
spokeswoman for the event.
   But the city's claim to glory could be fleeting. Battle Creek,
Mich., citizens will try to reclaim the title next month when they
convene to share their own mass breakfast.
   The Springfield eat-a-thon marked the 14th time that the city,
which is celebrating its 353rd birthday, has gone up against Battle
Creek.
   The rivalry dates to 1976, when Springfield promoters staged a
Bicentennial bid to wrest Battle Creek's record for the world
largest breakfast table.
   Last year, Battle Creek claimed a turnout of 32,000, and
Springfield had 31,279.
   The Michigan city had established its claim during celebrations
marking the 100th anniversary of the Kellogg Co. in 1952.
</TEXT>
