<FIRST>r a AM-BushCrashAnniversary     05-14 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Crash Anniversary,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky Town Remembers Its Dead From May 14, 1988, Bus Tragedy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Services scheduled to begin at 4 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grief returned Sunday to this close-knit
community, which marked the first anniversary of a fiery bus crash
that killed 24 teen-agers and three adults returning from a church
outing.
   ``Anniversaries are always bad,'' Mayor Joseph Hutcherson said.
``And of course, it's Mother's Day, too. That will have quite an
impact, I'm afraid.''
   Hutcherson said thousands of people were expected for
observances that were to include the unveiling of a monument
listing the victims of one of the worst bus crashes in U.S.
history. A memorial service also was scheduled at a high school
stadium.
   Because of parking limitations, those attended the observances
were being brought in from local shopping centers on school buses.
The irony was not lost on the Rev. Mark Denney, who heads the
Community Memorial Committee.
   ``I don't think there ever will be a bus outing in this
community that is planned without concern for that carefree outing
that became so tragic,'' Denney said.
   The old school bus, owned by the Radcliff First Assembly of God,
was carrying 67 passengers home for a trip to a Cincinnati
amusement Park when it was hit by a pickup truck going the wrong
way on Interstate 71 near Carrollton, Ky, on May 14, 1988.
   The truck driver, Larry Mahoney of Owen County, will be tried in
November on 27 counts of murder and count of driving while
intoxicated.
   The tragedy has prompted some in the community to campaign
against drunken driving.
   ``This is a crusade for me,'' said Army Sgt. Lee Williams, who
lost his wife and two daughters in the crash.
   Others said their goal has been simply returning to a normal
life.
   ``Drunk driving might be the worst thing in the world, but I
can't do anything about it now,'' said David Voglund, whose
13-year-old daughter was killed in the smashup.
   ``I'm still trying to distance myself from the whole thing
because I feel better that way,'' he said. Although he still thinks
about his daughter every day, Voglund said he has found an ally in
the passage of time.
   ``You don't feel nearly as lousy as you did six months ago,'' he
said. ``We're probably eventually going to be in pretty good shape.
Life does get better, or at least it has for us.''
</TEXT>
