<DOCNO> AP890514-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     05-14 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Congress, A Week of Helping the President ... And Clashing With
Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress offers a classic example of the
fickleness of politics this week as it considers a federal budget
worked out in advance with President Bush and a minimum wage
increase that sets lawmakers and the White House on a collision
course.
   The House and Senate will demonstrate how cooperative they can
be with the Bush administration when they consider the $1.17
trillion budget for fiscal 1990. Negotiators from the two chambers
completed work on a final version of the plan last Thursday, and
final passage of the spending plan is expected to be little more
than an exercise in rubber-stamping.
   The budget, for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, would hold
natural resources, transportation, agriculture and veterans
programs to growth rates below the rate of inflation. It would also
limit defense spending to $299.2 billion, $4.2 billion below what
would be needed to keep up with natural cost increases.
   But it would boost beyond inflation federal efforts for science,
education, and health programs. A looming dispute between Bush and
Democrats over how to collect $5.3 billion in additional tax
receipts has been postponed until later.
   Overall, the spending blueprint claims to compress the federal
deficit to $99.7 billion _ just within the $100 billion limit set
in the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget law.
   The harmony between the two branches was set in motion by a
deficit-reduction deal they reached last month. But when it comes
to their views on the minimum wage, Bush and the
Democratic-controlled Congress are anything but in harmony.
   Last Thursday, the House passed legislation that would increase
the $3.35-per-hour minimum wage to $4.55 by October 1991. The
Senate is poised to pass a similar measure this week, and Bush is
already threatening veto.
   The White House prefers a version that would limit the increase
to $4.25 by January 1992. Its version would also impose a
subminimum wage for six months, as opposed to the 60-day training
wage congressional Democrats prefer.
   Democrats seem unlikely to be able to muster the two-thirds
majorities in both houses that would be needed to override a veto.
But they are pressing the issue anyway in an attempt to position
themselves politically as the friend of the country's working class.
   More fireworks could come when Congress considers a domestic
spending bill with money for this year. Most of the money in it is
for veterans and for college loans, but the most controversial
provision would provide about $300 million this year for anti-drug
programs.
   Rep. Neal Smith, R-Iowa, chairman of the Appropriations justice
subcommittee, has said he wants to pay for the spending by using
part of the $650 million fine Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is
scheduled to pay for securities violations. Other lawmakers,
however, believe spending cuts must be made in other programs to
offset the drug spending.
   If the entire package contains too much new spending,
administration officials have said Bush might veto the measure. The
final size of the bill will not be known until early this week.
   The Senate also plans to vote on a resolution aimed at halting a
proposed deal between the United States and Japan to jointly
produce a new warplane.
   President Bush wants to move ahead with the $7 billion
arrangement, under which General Dynamics and Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries would jointly produce the FSX fighter. The plane, a
modernized version of the American F-16, would be deployed by Japan
in the late 1990s.
   The question has sparked debate between supporters who stress
the importance of U.S.-Japanese cooperation, and opponents who say
the proposal would cost American jobs and constitute a giveaway of
U.S. technology.
   A similar disapproval resolution has been introduced in the
House. If the measures are passed and vetoed by Bush, it would take
a two-thirds vote in each chamber to block the deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
