<FIRST>r e BC-Dance     05-14 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tharp Dance Uses Glass Music</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``In the Upper Room'' a plotless ballet
choreographed by Twyla Tharp to music by Philip Glass, is an
exhilarating, athletic work that doesn't give its American Ballet
Theater dancers a moment to stop.
   The dancers at the Metropolitan Opera are forever twirling,
traveling all over the stage.
   Watching ``In the Upper Room,'' one can be reminded of a time
when male dancers lifted women, hands on their waists, and set them
down again.
   In Saturday night's company premiere of ``In the Upper Room,''
Miss Tharp has choreographed seven ways to Sunday to lift
ballerinas, including one in which the dancer rolls around the back
of her partner's neck and slides down his other side.
   One of the most interesting variations has three ballerinas put
their arms over each other's shoulders, facing the audience like a
chorus line. Their partners pick them up, their legs dangling,
without breaking the lineup.
   The dance has nine parts; tempos vary. One has to be familiar
with Glass' music to discern melodies, but two of the sections
sounded like his opera ``Akhnaten.''
   The stage seemed to be in a fog, which sometimes poured from the
wings and at other times was done by gray lighting by Jennifer
Tipton.
   At first, the dancers were dressed in light gray with accents of
red _ red shoes, red socks and red belts. As ``In the Upper Room''
progressed, costumes, designed by Norma Kamali, became all or
mostly red.
   Twyla Tharp is artistic associate of the American Ballet
Theater, having disbanded her Twyla Tharp Dance troupe.
   The evening began with ``Les Sylphides'' with elegant,
effortless-looking dancing by Andris Liepa, a guest artist from the
Bolshoi Ballet. His partners were Cheryl Yeager, Julie Kent and
Leslie Browne. The corps de ballet, dancing like a dream in
floating white chiffon, is prominent in this 1908 ballet
choreographed by Michel Fokine to Chopin music.
   George Balanchine's ``Prodigal Son,'' choreographed in 1929 from
the Bible story to Prokofiev music, had Danilo Radojevic dancing
the title role with power and naivete. Cynthia Gregory was
glitteringly cold as the siren who tempts him, then tosses him to
her minions to rob and beat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
