<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sino-Soviet     05-14 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sino-Soviet,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Welcomes Gorbachev Visit to China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Sunday welcomed the
visit to China by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev as a sign
of improving Sino-Soviet relations, and also applauded the
restraint Chinese authorities had shown in dealing with recent
student demonstrations.
   President Bush within the past few days sent a message to
Chinese leader Deng Xiaopeng saying ``we welcomed the fact that the
People's Republic and the Soviet Union were getting together,''
said Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   ``It's not something that the United States ought to be worried
about,'' Baker said on the CBS-TV interview program, ``Face the
Nation.''
   In the past, Bush administration officials have welcomed the
apparent Sino-Soviet rapprochement as a step toward lowering global
tension.
   Baker also applauded restraint that Chinese authorities had
shown in dealing with thousands of students demonstrating in the
heart of Beijing.
   ``We take note of the fact that the authorities in Beijing have
really not, as they quite frequently have in the past, have not
cracked down on these demonstrations. These students have been
permitted to express their views rather freely, if you look at what
has been traditional in the past,'' he said.
   Baker added that ``we support freedom of expression around the
world. We support self-determination, freedom of expression,
democratization.''
</TEXT>
