<FIRST>r a AM-KlanTrial     05-14 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Klan Trial,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klansman Charged In Slaying Of Black Teen Goes On Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Ku Klux Klansman goes on trial this
week as an accomplice in the beating and hanging death of a young
black man _ a crime that has already resulted in a death sentence
against another man and a multimillion damage verdict for the
victim's mother.
   Benjamin Franklin Cox, 27, is charged with murder in the March
21, 1981, death of Michael Donald, 19, who was was abducted at
random from a Mobile street as part of a Klan conspiracy. He faces
up to life in prison.
   The killing led to a $7 million civil lawsuit verdict in 1987
that bankrupted the nation's oldest Klan group, the United Klans of
America. Donald's mother, Beulah Mae Donald, wound up acquiring the
Klan's headquarters in Tuscaloosa, the group's only major asset, in
partial payment. Mrs. Donald died last year.
   In 1983, Klan member Henry Francis Hays was convicted of capital
murder and sentenced to death in connection with the killing. And
ironically, a black civil rights group intervened on behalf of Hays.
   The NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, an offshoot of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, found
an Ohio lawyer willing to handle Hays' appeal. The group frequently
intervenes on behalf of indigent death row inmates.
   Cox faces the less serious charge of non-capital murder because
prosecutors have described him as an accomplice.
   Cox and Hays' father, Bennie Jack Hays, went on trial in
February 1988 on murder charges, but the elder Hays collapsed in
court, prompting a mistrial. This time, the two are being tried
separately, with Cox's trial scheduled to begin Monday.
   In the trial last year, the main prosecution witness was James
L. ``Tiger'' Knowles, who received a life prison sentence after he
pleaded guilty in 1983 to a federal charge of violating Donald's
civil rights.
   Knowles told how he and Henry Hays, 33, abducted Donald from a
downtown street and then beat him, bound him and put him in the
trunk of a car. Donald's body was found hanging in a tree in a
residential neighborhood in Mobile.
   Knowles testified that Cox provided a nylon rope used to hang
Donald. He also testified that the elder Hays ordered the killing
of a black as revenge for the mistrial of a black man who was
charged in the slaying of a white police officer in Birmingham.
   On Friday, a judge heard testimony at a hearing requested by
attorneys seeking to get Henry Francis Hays a new trial. His
attorney said he had new evidence that could warrant a new trial
and also that Hays was provided ineffective counsel at his first
trial.
</TEXT>
