<FIRST>r a AM-PostmasterTrial     05-14 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postmaster Trial,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Postmaster Gets Four Life Terms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLSBORO, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former postmaster accused of shooting
his wife and three sons to death and then trying to make it look as
though the eldest son had done the killings was found guilty of
murder and sentenced to four consecutive life sentences.
   Clinton County Judge Carson V. Brown Jr. imposed the sentence
Saturday on Bernon D. Shank after jurors became deadlocked over
what sentence to give the former postmaster from Lamar, in nearby
Clinton County. Brown moved the trial here, because of pre-trial
publicity.
   ``I'm very relieved,'' said Shank, who could have received a
death penalty from the jury. ``I'm still in a fog, really. I
haven't had too much time to think about it.''
   Shank, 41, was found guilty of first-degree murder in the
shooting deaths last May of his wife, Charlaine, 37; and sons
Christopher, 16; Bernon Jr., 14, and Ryan, 3. Each was shot in the
head at the family trailer.
   Peter Campana, Shank's attorney, said he planned to appeal the
verdict.
   The jurors deliberated about 4{ hours before sending a note to
Brown that they were deadlocked on the sentence.
   Brown was required by law to give Shank life sentences for each
first-degree murder. A life sentence in Pennsylvania has no parole.
   The jury found Shank guilty Friday after 27 hours of
deliberation over four days.
   Clinton County District Attorney Ted McKnight contended that
Shank wanted to start a new life with a family friend with whom he
had become romantically involved.
   He said Shank tried to frame his son Christopher by planting the
murder weapon and a ``suicide note'' next to the teen-ager's body.
   Shank steadfastly denied his guilt during three days on the
witness stand. He testified that Christopher had killed three
family members and then himself.
</TEXT>
