<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JohnBirch     05-14 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-John Birch,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ultraconservative Society Moves To America's Heartland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new executive director of the John
Birch Society insists that his conservative group's relocation to
the birthplace of the late Sen. Joseph McCarthy is nothing but a
``happy coincidence.''
   Community leaders, who have long dissociated themselves from
McCarthy's reckless anti-communism, agree that it's a coincidence,
although not one that makes everyone happy.
   ``It was more of an accident that Joe McCarthy was born here and
it's more of an accident that the John Birch Society is moving
here,'' said Michael O'Brien, a University of Wisconsin professor
who has written a book on the activities that led to McCarthy's
censure by the Senate in 1954.
   The Birch Society, a conservative political organization that
emphasizes anti-communism and reducing the size of U.S. government,
announced in March that it was closing its headquarters in Belmont,
Mass., and San Marino, Calif., and moving them to Appleton, a city
of 65,000 on the banks of the Fox River in east-central Wisconsin.
Employees are due to begin moving in this week.
   Since the announcement, city officials have repeatedly denied
that the arrival of the society will affect the city's image.
   ``I don't think anyone is frightened and certainly no one is
alarmed,'' Mayor Dorothy Johnson said. ``I don't think anyone will
be much affected by the coming of the John Birch Society. It's
fairly esoteric. We have people of all persuasions.''
   McCarthy, who was born in nearby Grand Chute, is not the only
Appleton-area native who has gained the town some notoriety. In
addition to the annual memorial at McCarthy's grave in St. Mary's
Cemetery, there is a seance each Halloween for the late magician
and escape artist Harry Houdini, who was born and raised here.
   But those events, city officials say, are oddities in what is
otherwise a typical Midwest community, a Republican stronghold,
that is gradually shedding its rural roots for a more urban
economy. Johnson, who has been mayor since 1980, calls it ``the
best of Middle America.''
   G. Allen Bubolz, 52, who stepped down as an executive at Secura
Insurance in Appleton to become executive director of the Birch
Society, said the group chose Appleton as its new headquarters
because he lives there, not because of the city's ties to
conservatism or McCarthy's legacy.
   However, he said, the fact that McCarthy was born there is a
``happy irony.''
   ``We're quite pleased because Sen. Joe McCarthy was a great
American, a stalwart of patriotism, a warrior of the evils of
communism. It's a happy coincidence,'' he said.
   The society was founded in 1958 by 11 men, including William J.
Grede, founder of Grede Foundries in Milwaukee, and Robert Welch, a
retired candy company executive. It was named after John M. Birch,
a Baptist missionary and U.S. Army captain who was killed by
Chinese communists a few days after World War II ended.
   The organization now claims ``several tens of thousands'' of
members who meet in local chapters around the nation, Bubolz said.
   He said the organization's militant anti-communism has given way
to a less aggressive style, although he stressed that the society's
underlying philosophy hasn't changed.
   Outagamie County Supervisor Ronald VanderVelden, who led a
futile fight to remove a life-size bust of McCarthy from the
courthouse in Appleton three years ago, said he's worried that the
Birch Society leaders might try ``integrating their philosophies
into state and local government.''
   But William J. Welch, president of the Fox Cities Chamber of
Commerce (and no relation to the Birch Society founder), dismissed
such worries.
   ``The last time I checked, the John Birch Society wasn't
advocating the violent overthrow of the United States government,''
Welch said. ``And quite frankly, if they have any problem it is
that people don't take them quite that seriously.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
