<SECOND>AM-BRF--Wolf Attack,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Staten Island Boy Attacked By Family's Pet Wolf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pet wolf that attacked and critically injured
a 3-year-old boy did not carry rabies, the Health Department said
Sunday.
   Timothy Bajinski underwent surgery Saturday at Staten Island
Hospital for severe lacerations in his head. The child was in
critical but stable condition, hosptial spokeswoman Arleen Ryback
said Sunday.
   The boy was alone in the back yard Saturday afternoon when the
10-year-old wolf attacked the youngster, said police spokesman Sgt.
Peter Berry. Police did not know what caused the animal to attack.
   After the attack began, the wolf was beaten to death with a
baseball bat by a friend of the child's mother, Susan Bajinski. Ms.
Bajinksi was issued a summons for violating health code regulations
that forbid wild animals to be kept in the city.
   The wolf ``tested negative for rabies,'' New York City Health
Department spokesman Marvin Bogner said.
