<DOCNO> AP890514-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 1606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TankerSpill-NTSB     05-14 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill-NTSB,0861</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Federal Authorities To Open Hearings On Oil Disaster</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When federal investigators open
hearings this week into the nation's largest oil spill, they will
be looking for answers to fundamental questions that so far have
stymied authorities.
   Coast Guard personnel, Exxon executives and crew members from
the tanker Exxon Valdez all face scrutiny as the National
Transportation Safety Board, in five days of hearings beginning
Tuesday, tries to solve these mysteries:
   _Why did the 987-foot tanker stray far from estabished shipping
lanes and rip its single-sheath bottom open on Bligh Reef, a
well-charted obstacle about 25 miles from Valdez?
   _Was the captain, Joseph Hazelwood, 42, of Huntington, N.Y.,
intoxicated at the time of the crash?
   _How long was the vessel stranded before the crew reported the
accident to the Coast Guard?
   _Did the crew's frenzied attempts to free the ship by
``rocking'' it off the reef widen the gash in the hull, spilling
still more oil into the icy water?
   _Did the Coast Guard, the oil industry, Exxon and state
officials react promptly to the emergency?
   The board's final report won't be completed for nine to 12
months, board spokeswoman Drucella Anderson said. ``We hope to
determine the probable cause and make some safety
recommendations,'' she said.
   Although the focus of attention shifts from Valdez to the
hearings in Anchorage this week, the hard work continued Sunday in
Prince William Sound where the accident took place and where crews
are still trying to clean fouled beaches.
   The Coast Guard continued its reconnaissance flights over the
spill. The flights were ordered to help halibut fishermen avoid
polluted areas on Monday, when their 24-hour commercial season
opens.
   ``Oil sightings will be relayed to fishermen by radio,'' Coast
Guard spokesman Dennis Hubbard said Sunday. ``Whatever we've got,
we're using. C-130s, helicopters, whatever.''
   It has been nearly two months since the catastrophe changed life
in what had been a quiet fishing village.
   The trouble began shortly after midnight on March 24, when the
Exxon Valdez, its 13 tanks filled with North Slope crude from the
trans-Alaska pipeline, slammed into a reef shrouded in darkness.
   The crippled vessel quickly began hemorrhaging oil _ by latest
estimate, 10.9 million gallons _ into the pristine waters of Prince
William Sound.
   The sound, named after the third son of England's King George
III, is one of Alaska's most popular and scenic recreational areas,
teeming with animals, fish and birds.
   The huge vessel, apparently maneuvering to avoid the glittering
ice chunks cast into the sound by Columbia Glacier, swerved from
its outbound lane and across the incoming zone, then continued
miles off course toward the submerged, jagged outcropping.
   Minutes before the crash the crew, apparently aware that their
vessel was at risk, frantically tried to avoid the reef, according
to an analysis of radio traffic between the Exxon Valdez and the
Coast Guard.
   Then, in the words of helmsman Robert Kagan, the Exxon Valdez
went for ``a bumpy ride.''
   As its massive hull scraped along the reef, it scooped up
boulders the size of automobiles and stuffed them into its huge oil
tanks.
   ``We've fetched hard aground. ... We're leaking oil. We're going
to be here a while. I just wanted to make a report,'' Hazelwood
radioed shortly after 12:20 a.m. As he spoke, the crude gushed into
the water.
   In the more than seven weeks since the crash, oil has spread
some 450 miles southwest of Valdez, fouling shorelines throughout
Prince William Sound and along the Alaska coast to Wide Bay, near
Kodiak Island. The oiled beaches include those of the spectacular
Katmai National Park.
   To probe the accident, the transportation board has assembled
what it describes as a panel of inquiry _ one board member to
conduct the proceedings, staff members and investigators to sift
the evidence and representatives of each ofthe four parties having
a direct interest in the proceedings.
   Those are the state of Alaska, Exxon, the Coast Guard and
Alyeska, the oil industry's jointly owned company that operates the
800-mile-long trans-Alaska pipeline.
   The chairman for the hearings is Lee Dickenson, the only member
of the board who will be present in Anchorage. Later, in
Washington, D.C., the full board will consider the evidence
developed from the Anchorage testimony.
   Unlike a court of law, the NTSB's rules specifically bar lawyers
from posing questions. Instead, representatives of each of the four
parties at interest directly question the witnesses, as does
Dickenson.
   Crew members from the Exxon Valdez are scheduled to testify
first, followed by Coast Guard personnel, representatives of Exxon
and Alyeska, and winding up on the final day with more Coast Guard
officials.
   One person who won't be at the hearings is Hazelwood, who
declined to testify but who offered information in writing to the
board. Hazelwood has been charged in an Alaska court with three
misdemeanor counts that include operating a vessel while drunk, and
his trial is scheduled to begin June 20 in Valdez.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
