<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-USTroops     05-14 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US Troops,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Soldiers Feel The Heat In Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP RUSSO, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army Spec. 4 Peter Lucas and his
buddies got a hot and humid welcome to Panama as they began to
settle into their posts Sunday near the Panama Canal.
   ``It's only 8 a.m. and it already feels like the hottest day of
the year in Minnesota,'' said the Duluth man as he ate breakfast
near a row of 10 armored personnel carriers.
   ``You guys ever have any breeze here?'' he asked.
   It was only 85 degrees, but Lucas and 150 men from the 5th
Infantry Division were camped in a steamy, windless jungle clearing.
   They are among the nearly 1,900 fresh troops dispatched by
President Bush to assure the security of the Panama Canal, U.S.
installations and American citizens.
   They arrived Saturday from Fort Polk, La., and Sunday morning
they were oiling and cleaning equipment following an intense
tropical downpour during the night.
   Lucas, who said he was a history student, said he was familiar
with Panama.
   ``I know that for once, we are here to support democracy. It
didn't use to be that way in the past. I know Panama was part of
Colombia and we supported the separatist movement and that's how we
made a deal about building the canal,'' he said.
   ``It's hot and humid,'' said Pfc. Craig Schoenfelder, 21, of
Pittsburgh. ``What other kind of weather you have?''
   Hot and dry, he was told. ``Can't wait 'til noon,'' he said.
   Spec. 4 Jorge Montes of Houston, a medic, said, ``We are here to
support Americans citizens and property and help other military
units.''
   Pfc. Larry Duckles of Stillwater, N.J., a grenadier, and Pfc.
Scott Deninski, of Alfred, N.Y., a machine gunner, were cleaning
their weapons.
   ``We are just doing our job protecting Americans,'' Duckles said.
   Pfc. Michael Grant of Chicago sat on the wet ground cleaning his
weapon and looked up to say, ``This place is nice from what I've
seen. I talked to some Panamanians last night and I doubt they'll
have to use us. They seemed friendly. They said, `glad you're
here.'''
   Grant said he knew about the problems between Panama and the
United States.
   ``We are a peacekeeping force. But I don't think they will have
to use us,'' he repeated.
   ``It boils down to the fact that we have a job to do and we are
here to do it,'' said Ricky Zimmerman of Hoboken, N.J., a division
cameraman. ``This looks like a beautiful country, but coming out of
the tent this morning felt like getting hit with a wet towel.''
   The ``tent'' was a 100-foot, inflatable, air-conditioned dome
where all 150 soldiers slept in cots Saturday night.
   ``It's nice in there,'' smiled Lucas. ``This is a volunteer
army. They have to be nicer to us.''
</TEXT>
