<FIRST>r i AM-SoccerViolence     05-14 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Violence,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Condemn `Weekend of Shame;' 255 Soccer Fans Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WARSHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and lawmakers on Sunday condemned a wave of
fan violence that broke out on the last full day of the English
soccer season. Authorities arrested 255 fans during and after the
matches.
   The incidents Saturday and early Sunday came less than a month
after 95 fans died during an April 15 stampede at a soccer game at
Hillsborough Stadium in Sheffield.
   ``What happened last night has brought the game back to its
knees,'' charged David Evans, a Conservative member of Parliament
and chairman of the Luton Town club.
   Fellow Conservative parliamentarian John Carlisle called the
violence a ``weekend of shame that reinforces the government's
determination to clean up soccer and rid the country forever of the
scourge of the football hooligan.''
   On Saturday, fans poured onto the field and briefly stopped the
Crystal Palace-Birmingham City match. Twenty-four fans were
arrested on charges that included drunkenness, threatening, assault
and drug possession. Sixteen people were hospitalized and two were
kept overnight, one suffering from knife wounds, police said.
   Later Saturday, 42 Birmingham fans were arrested after they
smashed dishes and furniture at a roadside diner in Toddington,
police said.
   ``The youths started charging about ... throwing people and
furniture about,'' said a Bedfordshire police spokesman on
condition of anonymity.
   About 200 youths _ mainly Sheffield United supporters _ went on
the rampage in Weston-super-Mare after seeing their team beaten 2-0
at Bristol City. Police said 27 people were arrested for fighting
and breaking windows.
   Elsewhere, 44 Leeds United supporters were arrested after a bar
fight after a match in Shrewsbury. A 25-year-old Leeds man was
hospitalized with serious head injuries, police said.
   At Portsmouth, 57 Chelsea fans were arrested after trouble
around the Fratton Park stadium, and 11 Plymouth supporters were
arrested for disorderly conduct on a train headed for a match at
Bournemouth.
   Police on Sunday arrested 50 passengers aboard a bus chartered
by Bristol Rovers fans. Authorities said about 30 of the drunken
fans had gone to a party in Tewkesbury on their way home from a
match and had injured two guests.
   Police in Birmingham said the behavior of the town's fans at
Crystal Palace in south London suggested they had short memories.
   ``One wonders, in the light of (the) Hillsborough (stampede),
what on earth these mindless idiots were thinking of,'' said deputy
chief constable Paul Leopold.
</TEXT>
