<FIRST>r a AM-US-SovietArt     05-14 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Art,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Joint Exhibit of Contemporary U.S.-Soviet Art Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first exhibit to bring together
works by contemporary Soviet and American artists opened to eager
viewers Sunday at the Modern Art Museum.
   The exhibition, called 10 Plus 10, includes 60 paintings by 20
artists _ 10 from the Soviet Union and 10 from the United States.
It will be the first such exhibit to tour both nations.
   Chief curator Marla Price said more than 200 visitors came
through the doors in the first hour of the exhibit's debut.
   Modern Art Museum Director E.A. Carmean said the show is the
first chance the Soviets have had to help organize and take part in
touring shows.
   ``They want to participate,'' Carmean said. ``They want to
change the rules about exhibition touring. And we got there just
when they decided they wanted to change them.''
   In November 1985, when President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev signed an agreement to further cultural
exchanges, work was already under way in Fort Worth for such an
exhibition.
   Dee Smith, president of InterCultura, a Fort Worth-based museum
services group, had been talking to State Department officials
about the possibility of U.S.-Soviet cultural exchanges.
   In June 1987, Smith met with Genrikh Popov, chief of the Soviet
Department of Fine Arts, and returned with several ideas for an
exhibition, including a show of contemporary art.
   The exhibition came together over cookies and tea when Carmean
and Smith met Popov in February 1988.
   ``10 Plus 10 epitomizes cultural dialogue more clearly than any
other exhibition we've done,'' Smith said. ``The exhibition is a
direct dialogue between two completely different cultures that are
meeting each other for the first time.''
   A $150,000 grant from the Dallas-based Meadows Foundation helped
underwrite 10 Plus 10.
   The exhibit includes works by David Bates of Dallas and
Christopher Brown of Oakland, Calif., as well as Ross Bleckner,
April Gornick, Peter Halley, Annette Lemieux, Rebecca Purdum, David
Salle, Donald Sultan and Mark Tansey, all of New York.
   Soviet exhibitors are Yurii Albert, Vladimir Mironenko, Yurii
Petruk, Leonid Purygin, Andrei Roiter, Sergei Shutov, Alexsei
Sundukov, Vadim Zakharov, Anatolii Zhuravlev and Konstantin
Zvezdochetov.
   After 10 Plus 10 closes in Fort Worth on Aug. 6, it will travel
to the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, the Albright-Knox Art
Gallery in Buffalo, N.Y., the Milwaukee Art Museum and the Corcoran
Gallery of Art in Washington D.C.
   Then 10 Plus 10 will be exhibited in the Artist's Union Hall of
the Tretyakov Embankment in Moscow, the State Picture Gallery of
Georgia in Tbilisi and the Central Exhibition Hall in Leningrad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
