<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Mack     05-14 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mack,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Who Co-Starred With Buster Keaton Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Marion is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silent film actress Marion Mack, a
small-town girl who went on to become a Mack Sennett bathing beauty
and Buster Keaton's co-star in the classic ``The General,'' has
died. She was 87.
   Miss Mack died May 1 of heart failure after a lingering heart
condition. She was buried Saturday in a private service.
   Miss Mack, whose real name was Joey Marion McCreery, was born in
Mammoth, Utah, and came to Hollywood in April 1920.
   ``I went to Mack Sennett's studio and they gave me a job right
away at $25 a week,'' she told the Los Angeles Times in a 1987
interview.
   As a bathing beauty, she appeared in a number of short films,
then went on to make comedies and features for other studios before
writing and starring in a semi-autobiographical film, ``Mary of the
Movies.'' She eventually adopted the screen name Marion Mack.
   Her best-known role was in Keaton's 1926 Civil War comedy, ``The
General,'' in which she played his estranged girlfriend, Annabelle
Lee, who is accidentally kidnapped by Yankee spies.
   She later abandoned acting to write scripts for her husband,
producer Louis Lewyn. In 1949, she entered the real estate business
and moved to Orange County, settling that year in Costa Mesa. Lewyn
died in 1969.
   ``The General'' was a critical and financial failure at the time
of its release but is now considered Keaton's masterpiece. When
interest in the film revived in the 1970s, Miss Mack was tracked
down by a film historian and made the rounds of film festival
screenings until illness forced her to quit.
   ``I enjoyed going back to traveling with the movie and being an
actress again,'' she said.
   Miss Mack is survived by her son, a stepsister and three
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
