<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Coelho-Ethics     05-14 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coelho-Ethics,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>No. 3 House Democrat Amends Report on Junk Bond Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tony Coelho acknowledged Sunday that a
California savings and loan executive set him up in a junk bond
investment that netted the congressman a $6,882 profit without him
having to put up any of his own money.
   Coelho released a detailed report of the arrangement, in which
the S&amp;L executive purchased the $100,000 in bonds for Coelho and
held them until Coelho could raise money to pay for them, in part
with a loan subsequently obtained from the executive's S&amp;L.
   Except for some reporting errors, Coelho said, the 1986 deal was
``totally above board.''
   The California congressman _ as majority whip the No. 3 Democrat
in the House _ released his attorney's review of the financial
transaction. The review was begun after The Washington Post last
month first reported on Coelho's investment in the high yield bonds.
   According to the report, Coelho first considered investing his
1986 campaign funds in 12{ percent bonds, based on a suggestion by
Thomas Spiegel, chief executive officer of the Columbia Savings and
Loan Assn. of Beverly Hills, Calif.
   Although Coelho ruled out that type purchase for his campaign,
Spiegel suggested that Coelho himself could make an investment in
the bonds, which were being issued for a corporate takeover.
   When Coelho could not come up with the $100,000 by the required
purchase date of May 5, Spiegel bought the bonds himself and held
them for a month while Coelho completed his financing _ half of
which came from Spiegel's bank.
   At that point, Coelho bought the bonds from Spiegel and paid him
interest equivalent to what the bonds made during that period. When
the congressman sold the bonds in October, 1986, he was able to pay
back his loans and realize a $6,882 profit in four months.
   Coelho's lawyer, Robert F. Bauer, concluded that Spiegel's role
could not be construed as a ``gift'' which would violate House
rules, since Coelho paid him interest. He also said the original
issuing of the bond to Coelho's campaign committee, instead of the
congressman, was a clerical error.
   Coelho spokesman David Dreyer said the report was given Friday
to the House ethics committee, which routinely reviews House
financial reporting compliance. He said the amended financial
disclosure was to be filed Monday.
   There is no indication whether the ethics committee is
considering or plans to review the bond purchase.
   Coelho insisted in his statement that the deal was proper but
said he regretted it.
   ``The report shows that although my purchase of the bonds was
lawful, appropriately financed and that no questions about `gifts'
can be fairly raised, my 1986 financial disclosure form was
incomplete and contained some reporting errors,'' Coelho said.
   ``I am accepting without reservations the conclusion of my legal
counsel that the purchase of the bonds was totally above board,''
he said.
   ``Public officials are today, however, living in a period of
intense questioning. ... With the benefit of hindsight, I now
regret having made this transaction.''
   Coelho, who has ambitions of climbing higher in the House
leadership, last year put all of his holdings into a blind trust.
``My greatest regret is not having gotten into the blind trust
sooner,'' he said Sunday.
   Dreyer said the congressman's staff had spent a month ``to
understand fully and reconstruct this transaction'' instead of
releasing details piecemeal. He said the effort did not include
checking whether Spiegel had any interest in legislation, because
that is only an issue if Spiegel had conferred a gift.
   ``We don't think it's going to end up as a big deal,'' he said
of the transaction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
