<DOCNO> AP890514-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 1801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People-CEOPay     05-14 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-CEO Pay,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney's Eisner Is America's Highest-Paid CEO, Forbes Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Hold for release at 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source. A version
of this story also moved on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael D. Eisner, the head of Walt Disney
Productions, doesn't get Mickey Mouse pay. He received more than
$40 million in compensation last year, making him by far America's
best paid chief executive officer, says Forbes magazine.
   The Los Angeles executive took top honors in the cover story in
Forbes' upcoming May 29 issue on the nation's 800 best paid CEOs,
rising from No. 14 in last year's survey.
   Forbes considered such things as stock option plans in addition
to salaries and bonuses in putting together its list.
   Eisner received $7,506,000 in salary and bonuses plus
$32,588,000 in stock gains in 1988 for a total of $40.1 million.
   ``He's been able to build a company that can do incredible
creative work, and he is equally good with implementation,'' said
Apple Computer CEO John Sculley, who came in ninth with about $9.49
million in compensation.
   Far back in second place was Steven J. Ross of Warner
Communications Inc., who had about $14.16 million and was in 48th
place last year. Richard L. Gelb of Bristol-Myers Co. was third at
about $14.14 million, rocketing up from 165th place.
   Rounding out the top 10 were: William P. Stiritz of Ralston
Purina Co. ($13 million), Paul B. Fireman of Reebok International
Ltd. ($11.44 million), James D. Robinson III of American Express
Co. ($11.24 million), Donald E. Petersen of Ford Motor Co. ($10.49
million), Kenneth H. Olsen of Digital Equipment Corp. ($9.98
million), Sculley and Michael W.J. Smurfit of Jefferson Smurfit
($9.25 million).
</TEXT>
