<FIRST>u i AM-Syria-Egypt     05-14 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Syria-Egypt,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syria Welcomes Egypt Back to Arab Fold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria on Sunday welcomed Egypt's return
to the Arab fold, saying Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
expected participation at an Arab League summit in Morocco was a
positive development.
   Presidential spokesman Jibran Kourieh issued a statment saying
``Syria supports and approves the return of Egypt to its natural
place in the struggle'' against Israel.
   Egypt was isolated from the 22-member Arab League and most Arab
nations severed relations with Egypt after it signed the Camp David
peace accords with Israel in 1979.
   But in the past two years all but three of the countries,
hardline Syria and Libya and war-divided Lebanon, restored ties.
   Syrian Oil Minister Mutanius Habib said last week Syria did not
object to Egypt's return to Arab organizations. He spoke during a
meeting in Kuwait of the Organization of Arab Oil Exporting
Countries in Kuwait. Egypt was readmitted to that organization on
Saturday.
   Kourieh's statement did no specifically mention the Arab League
but made clear Syria would no longer oppose Egypt's participation.
   He said Syrian President Hafez Assad and Mubarak were ``old
friends,'' and Assad ``is aware that President Mubarak is not Anwar
Sadat.'' President Sadat signed the Camp David pact, making Egypt
the first Arab country to agree to peace with Israel. He also made
a historic journey to Jerusalem.
   Mubarak became president after Sadat was assassinated by Moslem
fundamentalist extremists in October 1981.
   ``Syria asserts that the presence of President Mubarak at the
summit is a positive development,'' Kourieh said.
   An Arab League summit is scheduled for May 23-24 in Casablanca,
Morocco.
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi has said he would not attend
the summit if Egypt is invited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
