<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-14 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Rockies and in South and Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms brought heavy rain and hail to the Rockies on
Saturday and also soaked parts of the South and Northeast. Some
snow fell in the West.
   Showers and thunderstorms spread over Colorado, spattering
Colorado City and Denver with hail. Locally heavy rain fell in
portions of the central Rockies, and a flash flood watch was posted
for parts of southern Wyoming.
   Severe thunderstorms were expected further south in the southern
high Plains. Tornado watches were posted for northeast and
east-central New Mexico and a large part of western Texas.
   Thunderstorms were scattered throughout the day across much of
Arkansas, Mississippi, western Tennessee and Alabama. Some hail was
reported in Oldham County, Ken.
   Thunderstorms also developed over southeast Florida and along
the Georgia and Carolina coast.
   Showers reached across portions of the middle and northern
Atlantic coastal states, with thunderstorms over central and
western Pennsylvania and New York state.
   In Maine, however, swollen rivers began to recede after forcing
some precautionary evacuations and flooding several roads in the
central and southern parts of the state.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included almost an inch at Meridian, Miss., and two-thirds of an
inch at Savannah, Ga.
   Snow fell over higher elevations in the western states Saturday
and Sunday. An inch of snow was on the ground Sunday morning
between Flagstaff and Winslow, Ariz., and 6 inches fell at Duck
Creek, Utah. Portions of Yellowstone National Park received 2
inches overnight.
   Skies were generally clear over the Pacific Northwest and partly
cloudy from the Dakotas across the upper Mississippi Valley to
Michigan. Skies were sunny in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 41
degrees at Lander, Wyo., to 94 degrees at Laredo, Alice and
Beeville, all in Texas.
   The low in the nation Sunday morning was 21 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
   The forecast for Monday included showers and thunderstorms from
Texas across the lower Mississippi Valley, Gulf Coast states and
the central and southern Appalachians to the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast. Rainshowers were expected over New England, New
York, Pennsylvania and eastern Michigan, with showers and
thunderstorms forecast over western portions of the central and
southern Plains and across most of the mountains of the West.
   Afternoon high temperatures were expected to be in the 50s over
the northern and central Rockies and western Pennsylvania; in the
80s over western Minnesota and portions of the Dakotas, from the
south Atlantic Coast across Florida and the central Gulf Coast
region, and across most of Texas and the desert Southwest to
interior valleys of California; and in the 90s along the Rio Grande
in Texas. Elsewhere, highs were expected in the 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
