<FIRST>r a AM-People-NorthJury     05-14 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-North Jury,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Jury Forewoman Was Cousin of Prosecutor's Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury forewoman in the Oliver North trial
said her undisclosed kinship to the secretary of a prosecutor in
the case did not affect her judgment or her decisions.
   ``She knew her job, and I knew mine. Just because she worked for
(prosecutor John) Keker didn't mean diddlywink,'' forewoman Denise
Anderson said in an interview in the May 22 issue of People
magazine.
   In a courthouse elevator during the trial, Ms. Anderson bumped
into Gertrude Griffin, a cousin who Ms. Anderson had learned was
working as a secretary for Keker.
   Ms. Anderson said the two did not discuss the case and she did
not report the meeting or the relationship to Judge Gerhard Gesell.
   The forewoman and her 11 fellow jurors found North, a former
Marine colonel and National Security Council staffer, guilty of
three felony counts and acquitted him of nine others.
   In the interview, Ms. Anderson, a 34-year-old hospital
administrative secretary, said reaching the decision was a
stressful, nerve racking and divisive process that left her feeling
alienated from the other jurors.
   ``A lot of times I would come back to my (hotel) room, shut the
door and just cry,'' she said.
   When she requested additional copies of the judge's instructions
and trial evidence, Ms. Anderson said some of her colleagues were
angered.
   ``Some people fought me on it. They didn't want to read. They
didn't want to discuss,'' she told the magazine.
   Later, when she asked for larger quarters in which to work
without consulting the other jurors, ``they began cussing me out.''
   ``We didn't have time for politeness,'' she said. ``A man's life
was in our hands.''
   The panel couldn't even agree on rest breaks.
   ``I figured we were taking too much time off, (but) they wanted
to take more breaks and goof off,'' she said.
   In the end, she said, her prodding paid off.
   The jury ``did the work because they realized it was
important,'' and ``we had some good conversations and good
arguments.''
   She said the jurors saw North as a scapegoat who followed the
orders of his bosses. She admitted she was concerned about the
stiff sentence North faces, including 10 years in jail and $750,000
in fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
