<FIRST>r i AM-China-Reporter'sNotebook     05-14 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Reporter's Notebook,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Protesters Bring Own Glee Club, First Aid Squad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A harsh midday sun beat down Sunday on
hunger-striking students in central Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   Some napped after a sleepless night of chanting and singing;
others sat listless amid discarded plastic water bottles and torn
newspapers.
   Then the first stirring musical notes broke the calm. The
Beijing College of Aeronautics' glee club had arrived.
   Several dozen students, led by their conductor, lined up in
front of the strikers and began to sing the ``Internationale,'' the
socialist anthem that has become the hit song of the month-long
students' democracy movement.
   Heads raised, a few strikers joined in.
   The glee club sang the anthem a few times and the performance
ended to cries of ``Thank you!''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Speaking of singing.
   Late Sunday, students demanded that Communist Party chief Zhao
Ziyang and Premier Li Peng address them from the center of
Tiananmen Square.
   But what could they say to appease the student anger over
corruption and official incompetance?
   ``Make them sing,'' said one student.
   ``And make it the Internationale,'' said another.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Students from Beijing Medical University donned white coats and
arm bands and established a first-aid squad.
   ``The first symptoms will be headache,'' said one young man, who
like many others feared to give his name because of possible
reprisal. He and his colleagues set up shop amid boxes containing
aspirin, packets of Chinese medicines and bottles of glucose.
   ``We'll be needed,'' they predicted early in the first full day
of the hunger strike, and they were. As a strong sun blazed down on
the square the first-aid team moved among their fellow students and
handed out pills.
   ``If they fall down fainting, and they are in real danger, we'll
send them out,'' said one member. ``But if someone insists on
persisting and won't go, we have to accept it.''
   At least 10 students were carried Sunday afternoon to a nearby
city ambulance, suffering from dehydration and too much sun.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Workers who have cheered the students during earlier protests
and occasionally accompanied them demonstrated their support again.
Two groups with about 200 people in each each paraded around the
square before dawn Monday under banners proclaiming themselves the
``Capital Workers Group'' and chanted, ``Long live the students!''
   Several joined the hunger strikers.
   ``I've been marching with the students since (April) 18th,''
said a fasting construction worker. ``My boss has chewed me out ..
. and my wife opposes it too. But I'm concerned about democracy. We
workers should be the masters.''
   He said other workers ``are waiting. If there is bloodshed, they
will rise up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
