<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-14 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Opens Detour to Bypass Rebel-threatened Highway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of trucks on Sunday rumbled
along a dirt road built to bypass a section of the major supply
route to the capital that is frequently cut by anti-communist
rebels.
   The 18-mile detour runs across flat planes, unlike the main
Salang highway that weaves through the mountains between Kabul and
the Soviet border, 260 miles away.
   Soldiers stationed at a checkpoint on the outskirts of Kabul
said the new road was opened Wednesday and it has been used by more
than 1,000 privately operated trucks. They said about 200 trucks
reached Kabul Sunday.
   There are government checkpoints every 1.5 miles along the
detour, according to the soldiers.
   Guerrillas in the mountains north of Kabul often attacked
convoys on the Salang highway, causing a shortage of food, fuel and
other essential supplies in the capital.
   ``The government controls this road,'' said one driver,
42-year-old Ghulabb, as his truck passed through the checkpoint to
enter Kabul. The truck was hauling three cars and auto parts with
firewood, bags of rice and cans of gasoline piled on top.
   Ghulabb, who uses only one name, said he left the Soviet border
Friday and made the journey to Kabul in two days.
   But finding drivers to make the hazardous trip is difficult and
owners must pay high wages to ge supplies delivered.
   Ghulabb said he earns the equivalent of about $500 per month,
which is more than double the average annual income in Afghanistan.
   Ghulabb, the father of five children, said he does not worry
about getting caught in the crossfire between rebels and government
troops.
   ``I've been driving for 16 years and haven't been fired on
yet,'' he said. ``Someone controls the road and someone wants to
use the road and it's how you make your deal.''
   When the rebels intensified their attacks on the Salang highway
in January the Soviet Union began an airlift to Kabul to overcome
severe shortages.
   The airlift is continuing with as many as 50 military transport
planes flying into Kabul daily with food, fuel, weapons and
ammunition.
   The Soviet Union sent military personnel into Afghanistan in
December 1978 to help the Marxist government battle the rebels and
for several years had more than 100,000 soldiers in the country.
   The Soviets agreed to withdraw under an Afghan-Pakistani
agreement and Soviet officials said all of their soldiers had left
the country by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
