<FIRST>r a AM-EasternArrest     05-14 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Arrest,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Claims `Bust Lorenzo' Hat Got Him Arrested On Eastern Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 28-year-old button collector says he was kicked
off an Eastern Airlines jet after he put on a ``Bust Lorenzo'' hat,
but airport officials say he was arrested for criminal trespass.
   Atlanta police Lt. Eugene Bell said John Zaubler, 28, of New
York was arrested on the misdemeanor charge following the incident
Thursday and later released on bond.
   Mark Coates, a supervisor with airport operations at Hartsfield
Atlanta International Airport said Zaubler was arrested after he
refused to sit in his assigned seat on the Eastern flight from New
York to Florida.
   Coates said Eastern personnel ``asked him to sit in the seat and
he didn't want to sit there. ... Then he refused to leave the
airplane.''
   Eastern officials called the police who arrested Zaubler, Coates
said.
   Coates said he did not believe the incident was related to the
ongoing strike against Eastern Airlines, which has been
characterized by bitter disputes between union workers and Frank
Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp.
   Zaubler, however, gave a different version of events in an
interview Sunday in New York City.
   Zaubler said he had gotten off the jet during a layover in
Atlanta. At the airport terminal, Zaubler saw pickets with ``bust
Lorenzo'' buttons and, as a collector of about 50,000 political
buttons, he asked for and was given one. Then, he said, he paid a
picket $5 for a ``bust Lorenzo'' cap.
   Zaubler, a real estate executive, said he wore the button and
cap into the Eastern terminal and finally took them off after
repeated objections from Eastern personnel.
   When he got back on the plane, he said someone was sitting in
his seat and some passengers had taken his three bags from the
overhead compartment and were going through his possessions.
   He said Eastern ticket agents on the plane refused to help him
and ordered him to sit somewhere else, telling him the flight now
had open seating so the seat assignment on his boarding pass from
New York no longer was valid.
   ``I put the Lorenzo cap back on for 15 seconds,'' he said.
   At that point, he said, one of the ticket agents told him:
``That's it. You're off the plane.''
   Zaubler, who described himself as a conservative Republican who
thinks ill of unions and has ``tremendous respect'' for Frank
Lorenzo, said he apologized but was taken off the plane by police
officers and arrested.
</TEXT>
