<FIRST>u a AM-LATeachers     05-14 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Strike Looms With No Last-Minute Reprieve in Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers cast aside any chances for a
last-minute resolution of their lengthy labor dispute with the
school district and spent Sunday readying picket signs and rallying
the troops.
   ``We've got our people all across the district making phone
calls to their teachers telling them to be ready for the picket
line,'' said Catherine Carey, spokeswoman for United Teachers-Los
Angeles.
   Board of Education President Roberta Weintraub said the district
would make no last-ditch contract offer.
   Despite the consensus that a strike was imminent, Ms. Weintraub
said she expected teachers to back down and settle before the
midnight strike deadline.
   ``The reality of the offer _ which is one of the best in the
nation, quite frankly _ is what makes me optimistic,'' Ms.
Weintraub said. ``With the variety of things we see on the table,
it is very unusual to have a strike.''
   The walkout was set to begin Monday, with hastily hired
substitutes crossing picket lines to teach the district's nearly
600,000 students.
   With five weeks remaining before summer vacation, the strike
threatened to create havoc with students' final grades. But
teachers stood by their demands for higher pay and more say in how
schools are run.
   ``We have not received any indication from the school district
that they want to come to the bargaining table,'' Ms. Carey said.
   Teachers have been adamant in their demand for a two-year
contract with a 21 percent pay hike. They also want elimination of
unpaid, non-teaching duties like school yard supervision and
after-school meetings, and more influence in how their schools are
run, an issue known as teacher governance.
   The district has offered teachers a 21.5 percent pay raise
spread over three years and a teacher governance plan that union
leaders have dismissed as tilted in favor of administrators.
   No formal bargaining talks took place during the weekend. Union
and district officials talked informally but were unable to arrange
any formal resumption of negotiations, leading to gloomy
predictions about any hope of settling the dispute.
   ``It looks like it's going to happen,'' said Pat Spencer,
spokesman for the Los Angeles Unified School District. ``We have
been preparing and planning for this for two months.''
   The district conducted mass hirings of substitutes, as teachers
marched outside recruiting centers carrying picket signs bearing
messages such as ``this is no way to begin a teaching career.''
   Hundreds of people responded to the district's call for
emergency substitutes, but the number fell far short of
replacements needed for the thousands of teachers expected to
strike.
   Ms. Weintraub warned teachers that their benefits would lapse
Monday if they strike, unless they paid $270.83 a month from their
own pockets.
   Los Angeles Unified School District, with about 800 schools
serving 594,000 students, is second only in size to New York City
and hasn't been struck by teachers since a 23-day walkout in 1970.
   United Teachers-Los Angeles, which represents about 22,000 of
the district's 32,000 teachers, nurses and counselors, has been
locked in the contract battle with the district for more than a
year.
   State and local elected officials stayed out of the dispute
until last week when Senate President Pro Tem David Roberti, D-Los
Angeles, said the district would get at least $34 million, and
possibly as much as $60 million in new revenue that could be used
for higher teacher salaries.
   But district officials refused to raise their offer based solely
on projections of funds that might be received.
   In March, teachers overwhelmingly rejected a 20-percent pay
raise over three years, effectively stalling negotiations despite
the efforts of a state mediator.
   Teachers salaries start at $23,440 and can go as high as $43,319.
   Administrators' salaries range from $37,000 to $95,600. District
Superintendent Leonard Britton, who has been criticized by union
leaders for his perceived hard-line attitude, receives an annual
salary of $141,000.
</TEXT>
