<FIRST>r i AM-Shakespeare'sHaunt     05-14 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shakespeare's Haunt,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actors Campaign to Save Remains of Elizabethan Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shakespearean actors took to a makeshift stage
Sunday in a bid to block construction of an office building at the
site of a 16th century theater where the Bard himself once
performed.
   The players entertained a rally that attracted hundreds of
supporters to the remains of the Rose Theater on the south bank of
the River Thames.
   ``It's like the Greeks knocking down the Parthenon to make a car
park,'' Sir Peter Hall, former director of the National Theater,
said at the rally.
   ``I do not believe any other country at this moment in the world
would do this and it's a terrifying example ... of a situation in
our country where cash is more important than the soul of the
country itself,'' he said.
   On the makeshift stage a few yards from the Rose, members of the
Royal Shakespeare Company read from William Shakespeare's ``Henry
VI,'' which they now are performing in London.
   Shakespeare is thought to have acted in ``Henry VI'' at the
Rose. His early plays were staged there.
   Bulldozers were scheduled to begin work on an office building at
the site Monday morning. Construction has been postponed for five
months since the remains of the theater were found.
   Archaeologists pressed ahead with their excavation Sunday, and
protesters declared they would conduct an all-night vigil.
   The effort to save the theater site has attracted the support of
American actor Dustin Hoffman, who is in London to perform in
Shakespeare's ``The Merchant of Venice.'' Other dramatic luminaries
who have called for preserving the site include actors Laurence
Olivier, Derek Jacobi, Ian McKellen, Dame Peggy Ashcroft, Dame Judi
Dench and playwright Tom Stoppard.
   Environment Secretary Nicholas Ridley, whose responsibilities
include the ancient monuments, said Friday he had not yet decided
what to do.
   The developers have said the work will cause ``minimal damage''
to the remains of the theater.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told the House of Commons
Thursday, ``Everything possible must be done to preserve the
theater .... There have been very constructive discussions between
the developers, English Heritage (a body that preserves historical
sites), and the Museum of London, with the result that the remains
are going to be preserved with the minimum of damage.''
   However, Hedley Swain of the Museum of London said Sunday: ``We
do not feel that their idea of preservation is very suitable. A lot
of the site will be irreplaceably damaged.''
</TEXT>
