<FIRST>r i AM-China-Sketches     05-14 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Sketches,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sketches of Summit Personalities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of the major participants
in the May 15-18 summit between Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and China's leaders.
   
   _Gorbachev, 58, was elected general secretary of the Soviet
Communist Party in 1985 and initiated major changes.
   In domestic affairs he made sweeping leadership changes to gain
backing for his policies of glasnost, or opening, and perestroika _
restructuring of the economy.
   In foreign policy he put the West on the defensive with his
initiatives on arms control. He withdrew Soviet troops from
Afghanistan, eased Kremlin controls over the Soviets' Eastern
European allies and improved relations with the United States and
Western Europe.
   In 1988 the Supreme Soviet elected Gorbachev president.
   ---
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Deng Xiaoping, 84, is the most powerful leader in China even
though the highest ranking position he holds is chairman of the
Central Military Commission of the ruling Communist Party.
   Deng was purged twice by radicals during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution and then staged a comeback that turned China around.
   He transformed a country dominated by ideological battles into
one with pragmatic, market-oriented economic policies.
   Living standards have improved for millions of Chinese but the
modernization drive has led to serious problems of inflation and
corruption.
   Deng wears a hearing aid and smokes heavily but is not known to
have any serious health problem. There are persistent rumors he
will retire from all his offices after the Gorbachev visit.
   ---
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Zhao Ziyang, 69, general secretary of the Chinese Communist
Party since 1987, has been the nation's leading advocate of rapid
economic reforms.
   As governor of Sichuan province in the late 1970s he led the
country in successful experiments in restoring family farming.
   In 1980 Deng brought him to Beijing and he was quickly named
premier. He held that post until 1987 when he became party chief
following the ouster of fellow reformist Hu Yaobang who was blamed
for student unrest.
   ---
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Li Peng, 60, premier since April 1988. An electric engineer he
studied in the Soviet Union in the 1950s and represents the
technocrats now filling many government offices.
   He has opposed Zhao's moves in market-oriented reforms, saying
he supports the plan but prefers a more cautious pace. Last
September after the inflation rate exceeded 30 percent Li called
for a two-year economic slowdown.
   ---
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Yang Shangkun, 81, became China's president, or head of state,
in April last year.
   Yang, a career military man, was active in Red Army campaigns in
the 1930s and 1940s and was appointed permanent vice chairman of
the Central Military Commission in 1982. He backed Deng's 1985
decision to end the wartime footing of the army and reduce the
force of more than 4 million soldiers by 1 million.
   The post of president is largely ceremonial but Yang does have
influence because of his close ties to Deng and his seat on the
17-member party Politburo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
