<FILEID>AP-NR-05-14-89 2230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Cheney-Commencement     05-14 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-Commencement,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Says Diplomacy Must Be Used In Removing Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomacy must be used if Panamanian leader
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega is to be removed from power, Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney said Sunday.
   Cheney, adopting a moderate tone a day after President Bush
urged the Panamanian people to drive Noriega from power, said
support from other South American leaders would help the
administration's efforts to encourage the general's departure.
   ``I think whatever you do is going to have to be done
diplomatically,'' the former Wyoming congressman said at
commencement exercises at the University of Wyoming.
   ``It would help if the other Latin American nations would come
together and make it clear that they won't deal with a Panamanian
government headed by Mr. Noriega.
   ``The Organization of American States will meet next week. If
they take a tough, strong position and join in supporting, for
example, the U.S. economic sanctions, those kinds of things might
conceivably, ultimately result in his departure,'' he said.
   Cheney praised Bush for his decision to send U.S. troops to
Panama in the wake of Noriega's efforts to nullify the results of
an election in which the general's handpicked candidates were
defeated.
   ``I think it was a necessary move, it was a step that a prudent
man would take,'' he said. ``We've got some 40,000 Americans who
live in Panama, we've got major obligations ... under the Panama
Canal Treaty.
   ``Hopefully, the situation will be resolved peaceably. Mr.
Noriega should obviously step down and let the people of Panama
prevail in terms of the election,'' he said.
   Cheney said the United States would like to avoid violence, but
added that the country has a commitment to protect the Panama Canal
under the treaty.
   ``That commitment runs to the end of the century and the
president, as commander-in-chief, has an obligation to carry out
the treaty responsibilities and also to safeguard American lives,''
he said. ``I think it is important that Noriega understand that we
are there specifically to see to it that we enforce our rights
under the treaty.''
   Cheney, who was honored as a ``distinguished alumni'' of the
university, also said he hopes Congress will increase defense
spending in the future.
   ``Everybody has this myth in mind that somehow we had this
massive arms buildup in the 1980s and it's been growing year by
year,'' he said. ``It did grow in the early 1980s, but it's been
stable to downhill ever since. If you keep cutting the defense
budget, we'll end up sooner or later with less military
capability.''
</TEXT>
