<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrash-Anniversary 2ndLd-Writethru a0758 05-14 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash-Anniversary, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0758,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceremonies Mark First Anniversary of Kentucky Bus Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with other services, governor attending,
telegram from President Bush; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young survivors of a bus crash that left 24
children and three adults dead helped unveil a black granite
monument Sunday, one of three ceremonies marking the first
anniversary of the fiery tragedy.
   ``In some ways, today is worse than others. It's the first
anniversary combined with Mother's Day, of all things,'' Rev. David
A. Seamands of Asbury Theological Seminary told a televised
community memorial service.
   More than 1,000 people attended the service at North Hardin High
School's football stadium, which overlooks the cemetery where many
of the victims of the May 14, 1988, accident are buried.
   About the same number of people attended the first service
dedicating the monument at the cemetery, as well as the second
ceremony at the high school to thank those who helped victims'
families through the past year.
   The aging school bus was carrying 67 passengers home when it was
hit by a pickup truck going the wrong way on Interstate 71 near
Carrolton, about 100 miles northeast of here. It was the nation's
worst alcohol-related highway accident and one of the worst bus
crashes in U.S. history.
   The truck driver, Larry Mahoney of Owen County, will be tried in
November on 27 counts of murder and one count of driving while
intoxicated.
   At the football stadium Sunday, the Rev. W. Don Tennison, whose
Radcliff First Assembly of God church owned the bus, read the names
of the 27 victims ``whose lives were cut short so suddenly by a
drunk driver.''
   As each name was called, a family member placed a yellow rose on
one of 27 wreaths of yellow carnations. Gov. Wallace Wilkinson and
his wife, Martha, then placed roses on a larger wreath of yellow
roses and white carnations.
   Wilkinson promised to take any action necessary to prevent a
recurrence. ``Where stronger penalties are needed, then stronger
penalties we will impose,'' he said.
   Tennison pleaded for all to refrain from drinking and driving.
   President Bush, who attended a Republican fund-raiser the night
before in Woodford County nearly 70 miles to the east, declined an
invitation to attend the service but sent a lengthy telegram, which
was read aloud.
   The telegram called drunken driving ``a national tragedy,'' and
said laws against drunken driving must be strictly enforced.
   The monument dedicated in North Hardin Memorial Gardens consists
of raised triangular slabs sloping away from a benchlike
centerpiece. It bears the names of the 27 dead and 40 survivors _
as well as the emblem of Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
   ``We felt a positive statement must be made,'' said Roy Keith,
owner of the company that built the monument. The idea was for a
memorial that would remind viewers of ``the terrible blight of
drunken drivers,'' he said at the ceremony.
   The monument was unveiled by survivors Aaron Conyers, 16; Carey
Aurentz, 15; Katrina Muller, 14; and Harold Dennis, 15; as well as
sons of two of the adults who died: John Robert Pearman Jr., whose
father drove the bus; and Charles J. Kytta III, whose father was
the church's youth minister.
   The Rev. Gene Waggoner, pastor of Stithton Baptist Church in
this northern Kentucky city of about 14,000 people, prayed for
inner peace for those mourning the victims, but said ``we have
every reason to be bitter.''
   Kentucky's top state highway official said the government was
trying to ensure that the tragedy will not be repeated.
   Kentucky Transportation Secretary Milo D. Bryant renewed his
criticism of the state school board's refusal 11 days earlier to
require more stringent training of school bus drivers.
   That was a recommendation of a bus-safety task force appointed
by Gov. Wallace Wilkinson and chaired by Bryant. The school board
balked because the state did not provide the $250,000 the panel
estimated would be the cost of the extra training.
   ``I say that you cannot put a price on the safety of our
children,'' said Bryant, who did not mention the board by name.
   Bryant said he would ``fight to have another emergency door ...
on the left side of all new school buses,'' a move also opposed by
the state Department of Education.
</TEXT>
