<SECOND>AM-BRF--Space Shuttle,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stormy Weather Keeps Space Shuttle in El Paso</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT BLISS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A NASA Boeing 747 carrying the space
shuttle Atlantis back to Kennedy Space Center in Florida remained
grounded here Sunday because of stormy weather.
   ``The weather here is fine, it's the weather between here and
where it's going that's bad,'' said a spokesman for Biggs Army Air
Field, who declined to identify himself.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration jet, carrying
the space shuttle on its back, left Edwards Air Force Base, Calif.,
Saturday on the first leg of a flight to return to Kennedy Space
Center. It arrived in Fort Bliss early Sunday.
   The Fort Bliss spokesman said the jet planned to depart Monday
morning, weather permitting.
   Thunderstorms and some tornadoes plagued most of Texas over the
weekend.
