<FIRST>r i AM-Icewalk 1stLd-Writethru a0768 05-14 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Icewalk, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0768,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polar Trekkers End 620-mile Journey</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD time of arrival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international team of eight explorers completed
a 620-mile trek to the North Pole on Sunday despite poor visibility
and drifting ice that hampered their journey, expedition organizers
said.
   Organizers said the bad weather prevented a Twin Otter plane
from making the trip to pick up the explorers who completed their
journey at 3:38 a.m. EDT.
   ``They're just verifying their position by satellite,'' said
Wendy White, a spokesman for the trip, known as Icewalk. ``They
think they're at the Pole.''
   The explorers left Ellesmere Island in Canada's Northwest
Territories on March 20. They made their journey to draw attention
to pollution and the dangers of global warming, known as the
greenhouse effect.
   The team includes members from the United States, Britain,
Canada, the Soviet Union, Australia, West Germany and Japan.
   The mission was designed to be different from previous
expeditions by making use only of human power. The group planned
its mission with skis and sledges for supplies, but without
dogsleds or skimobiles.
   The mission has been led by Robert Swan, a British explorer who
walked to the South Pole with two other men in 1986. A successful
completion of the current trip would make him the first person on
record to walk to both poles.
   The trekkers are scheduled to hold a news conference Monday at
Resolute Bay in the Northwest Territories if they are able to
return by then.
</TEXT>
